This paper is likely to belong to the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category as it deals with the problem of tracking an object by a network of nodes. It also involves the estimation of the state and extension of the object, which is a common problem in control systems. 

The paper also involves computer vision techniques for tracking extended objects, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) sub-category. 

The Bayesian model used in the paper suggests that it could belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category, which often involves probabilistic models for decision-making. 

The use of variational Bayesian methods and the ADMM technique suggests that the paper could also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category, which often involves optimization techniques for learning models. 

Finally, the paper involves simulations to verify the effectiveness of the proposed model and algorithms, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category, which often involves the use of simulations to evaluate algorithms.
